         <div type="commentary" subtype="frontmatter" xml:space="preserve">
        <p>The piece consists of twenty-five lines, each (with the exception of the last) consisting of three parts, which are metrically equivalent. The first twenty-four lines represent the twenty-four letters of the alphabet, with each of the three parts of a line beginning with the same letter. Thus the three parts of line 1 begin with A, those of line 2 with B and so on. The hymn is in fact a metrical acrostic. In some cases the third part of a line is so damaged that the third acrostic letter, which surely can be assumed, is missing.</p>
      </div>
